{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"16abe4deffdcb54d","type":"text","text":"## Database Index Types\n\n### 1. B-Tree (The Default)\n\n- **What it is:** A self-balancing tree structure that keeps data sorted.\n    \n- **Use Case:** Best for **unique values**, **ranges** (`>`, `<`), and **exact matches** (`=`).\n    \n- **How it works:** It allows the DB to find a row in $O(\\log n)$ time instead of scanning the whole table $O(n)$.\n    \n- **Interview Tip:** Mention that B-Trees are the \"workhorse\"—if you don't specify a type, this is what you're getting.\n    \n\n### 2. GIN (Generalized Inverted Index)\n\n- **What it is:** An index that maps \"keys\" (like words or JSON keys) to the rows that contain them.\n    \n- **Use Case:** Essential for **JSONB** columns and **Full-Text Search**.\n    \n- **Why for JSONB?:** A B-Tree can't index the _inside_ of a JSON blob efficiently. GIN allows you to query `{ \"pigeon_name\": \"Pesto\" }` inside a complex metadata column instantly.\n    \n- **Trade-off:** GIN indexes are much slower to build and update than B-Trees because every time you insert a row, the DB has to update many \"keys\" in the index.\n    \n\n### 3. Partial Indexes\n\n- **What it is:** An index with a `WHERE` clause. It only indexes a subset of your data.\n    \n- **Example:** `CREATE INDEX idx_active_users ON users (email) WHERE active = true;`\n    \n- **Why use it?:**\n    \n    1. **Storage:** It’s much smaller than a full index.\n        \n    2. **Performance:** Faster updates since the DB ignores rows that don't meet the criteria.\n        \n- **Interview Tip:** Great for \"Soft Deletes.\" If 90% of your table is \"deleted\" (e.g., `is_deleted = true`), a partial index on only the active 10% makes your queries lightning-fast and saves massive disk space.\n    \n\n---\n\n## 💡 Summary Comparison\n\n|**Index Type**|**Best For**|**Typical Data Type**|**Size/Overhead**|\n|---|---|---|---|\n|**B-Tree**|Sorting, Ranges, Equality|Strings, Ints, Dates|Low|\n|**GIN**|Membership (`@>`), Text Search|JSONB, Arrays, TSVector|High|\n|**Partial**|Filtering frequent queries|Any (with a filter)|Very Low|\n\n---\n\n### Interview \"Pro\" Answer\n\n> \"While B-Trees handle 90% of standard CRUD, I use **GIN** for flexible schema requirements like JSONB metadata to avoid full table scans. If I have a specific business logic filter—like 'only show pending SMS messages'—I'll implement a **Partial Index** to keep the index size small and the memory usage efficient.\"","x":-2320,"y":-320,"width":880,"height":1309},
		{"id":"05bb4c3729688373","type":"text","text":"### 1. The \"Read\" Gain (The Benefit)\n\nThe database stops doing **Sequential Scans** (reading every block of data from the hard drive) and starts doing **Index Scans**.\n\n- **Impact:** A query that takes 5 seconds to scan 1,000,000 rows might take 5 milliseconds with an index.\n    \n- **Why?** It reduces **Disk I/O**. Disk access is the slowest part of any database operation; jumping straight to the \"Page Number\" saves the CPU from doing useless work.\n    \n\n### 2. The \"Write\" Latency (The Hidden Cost)\n\nEvery time you `INSERT`, `UPDATE`, or `DELETE` a row, the database has to do **double work**.\n\n- **The Process:** It writes the data to the table (the \"Heap\"), but then it must immediately jump over to the Index and re-sort/re-balance the tree to include the new value.\n    \n- **The Bottleneck:** If you have 10 indexes on one table, a single `INSERT` actually triggers **11 write operations** (1 for the table + 10 for the indexes).\n    \n- **Senior Insight:** This is why you never index \"Status\" columns that change every second (like `is_processing`). The constant index updates will crush your write throughput.\n    \n\n### 3. The Storage Tax\n\nIndexes are not just metadata; they are physical files stored on the disk.\n\n- **Bloat:** In some high-scale systems, the indexes can actually become **larger than the table itself**.\n    \n- **Memory Pressure:** Databases try to keep \"Hot Indexes\" in RAM (the Buffer Cache). If you have too many indexes, they won't all fit in RAM, forcing the database to swap to the slow disk, which kills the performance of _all_ queries.\n    \n\n---\n\n## 🛠️ How to \"Sell It\" in the Interview\n\nIf they ask: _\"Should we just index every column in the WHERE clause?\"_\n\n**Your Answer:**\n\n> \"No, because indexing is a balancing act. While it optimizes **Reads**, it adds **Write Latency** and consumes **Storage/RAM**.\n> \n> Instead of 'indexing everything,' I prefer to:\n> \n> 1. Use **Composite Indexes** to cover multiple columns in one tree.\n>     \n> 2. Use **Partial Indexes** to only index 'active' data, saving space.\n>     \n> 3. Use **EXPLAIN ANALYZE** to verify that the index is actually being used before committing to the storage overhead.\"\n>     \n\n---\n\n### 📓 Obsidian Summary Table\n\n|**Action**|**Impact with Index**|**Why?**|\n|---|---|---|\n|**SELECT**|🚀 Much Faster|$O(\\log n)$ lookup vs $O(n)$ scan.|\n|**INSERT**|🐌 Slower|Must update the B-Tree/GIN structure.|\n|**UPDATE**|🐌 Slower|Must move entries in the index if the column value changed.|\n|**DELETE**|🐌 Slower|Must remove the pointer from the index.|\n|**STORAGE**|📈 Higher|Indexes are separate physical files on disk.|","x":-920,"y":-320,"width":1000,"height":1380},
		{"id":"9ae32085f3fe39e0","type":"text","text":"Think of an index as the **Table of Contents** in a textbook. Instead of reading every single page to find a specific topic (**Sequential Scan**), you look up the page number in the index and jump straight to the data (**Index Scan**).\n\n---\n\n### 📋 The Interview Pitch\n\n- **Primary Purpose:** To speed up data retrieval by providing a pointer to the physical location of a row, reducing the amount of disk I/O.\n    \n- **The Trade-off:** While reads become lightning-fast, **Writes (Insert, Update, Delete) become slower** because the database must update both the table data and the index itself every time a change occurs.\n    \n- **Space Cost:** Indexes occupy physical disk space. A \"Senior\" approach is knowing not to index every column, but only those used in `WHERE`, `JOIN`, and `ORDER BY` clauses.\n    \n\n---\n\n### 🧠 Key Concepts for Obsidian\n\n|**Feature**|**Description**|\n|---|---|\n|**Complexity**|Reduces lookup time from $O(n)$ (Scanning everything) to $O(\\log n)$ (B-Tree search).|\n|**Selectivity**|Indexes work best on columns with high \"uniqueness\" (e.g., Email is great, Gender is poor).|\n|**Covering Index**|When the index contains all the data the query needs, the DB doesn't even have to look at the actual table (Index Only Scan).|\n\n**Pro Tip for Interview:** Mention that \"An index is a trade-off between **Read Performance** and **Write Latency/Storage**.\" This shows you understand the architectural impact, not just the syntax.","x":320,"y":-320,"width":760,"height":800},
		{"id":"4017e49f234676f6","x":-2000,"y":1100,"width":742,"height":720,"type":"text","text":"## 1. Auto-Incrementing Integers (INT / BIGINT)\n\nThink of these as the \"standard\" for internal, high-performance systems.\n\n### **Pros**\n\n- **Maximum Performance:** Databases love them. Because they are sequential, the B-Tree index stays \"compact.\" New rows are always added to the very end of the tree, which avoids expensive \"page splits.\"\n    \n- **Storage Efficient:** A `BIGINT` is only **8 bytes**. A UUID is **16 bytes**. Smaller keys mean more of your index fits in the RAM (Buffer Pool), making your whole database faster.\n    \n- **Human Friendly:** It’s much easier to debug `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = 42` than a long string of hex characters.\n    \n- **Faster Joins:** Comparing two numbers is CPU-cheap; comparing 36-character strings is relatively expensive.\n\n### **Cons**\n\n- **Security Risk:** They are predictable. If your profile is `myapp.com/user/100`, I can guess `user/101` exists. This is called an **Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR)** vulnerability.\n    \n- **Distributed Headache:** If you have two different servers (like a microservices setup) both trying to insert a user at the same time, they have to \"talk\" to a central database to find out what the next number is. This creates a bottleneck.\n    \n- **Merging Issues:** If you ever try to merge two databases (e.g., merging a \"UK\" database and a \"US\" database), you will have thousands of ID collisions."},
		{"id":"2668656907a147d5","x":-1170,"y":1120,"width":710,"height":660,"type":"text","text":"**## 2. UUID (Universally Unique Identifier)\n\nThe \"go-to\" for modern, distributed, or public-facing applications.\n\n### **Pros**\n\n- **Distributed Scalability:** You can generate a UUID on your **Node.js** server, in a **React Native** app offline, or on a Linux worker without asking the database for permission.\n    \n- **Privacy & Security:** They are non-guessable. This prevents attackers from \"scraping\" your data by just incrementing a number in the URL.\n    \n- **Safe Merging:** You can merge ten different databases into one tomorrow, and you will never have a duplicate ID.\n    \n\n### **Cons**\n\n- **Index Fragmentation (The \"B-Tree Killer\"):** Standard UUIDs (v4) are random. When you insert a random ID, the database has to shove it into the _middle_ of the B-Tree. This forces the database to \"split\" pages on the disk, which is slow and makes your index \"bloated\" and messy.\n    \n- **Storage Overhead:** They take up **2x to 4x more space** than an integer. On a table with 100 million rows, that extra space translates to gigabytes of wasted RAM and slower disk I/O.\n    \n- **Ugly URLs/Logs:** They make logs and URLs very long and hard to read.**"},
		{"id":"30842e2cc8d1d10f","x":-1980,"y":1900,"width":701,"height":620,"type":"text","text":"## The 2026 Winner: UUID v7\n\nIf you are in an interview or starting a new project (like your **SMS SaaS**), this is the \"Senior\" answer.\n\n**UUID v7** combines the best of both worlds:\n\n1. **It starts with a timestamp:** This makes it **sequential**. It behaves like an Integer in the B-Tree (fast inserts, no fragmentation).\n    \n2. **It ends with random bits:** This makes it **globally unique** and secure.\n    \n\n### **The Comparison Table**\n\n|**Feature**|**Integer (BigInt)**|**UUID v4 (Random)**|**UUID v7 (Time-based)**|\n|---|---|---|---|\n|**B-Tree Friendly**|✅ Best (Sequential)|❌ Worst (Random)|✅ Good (Sequential)|\n|**Distributed**|❌ No (Needs central DB)|✅ Yes (Stateless)|✅ Yes (Stateless)|\n|**Security**|❌ Poor (Guessable)|✅ Excellent|✅ Great|\n|**Storage Size**|8 Bytes|16 Bytes|16 Bytes|\n|**Human Readable**|✅ Yes|❌ No|❌ No|"}
	],
	"edges":[]
}